Attended a work event in the upstairs back room. Staff was very friendly and accommodating. Food was above average for an event and the atmosphere was perfect for socializing. Highly recommend.

The pizza was amazing So one star for that. (And one star for the woman checking the tickets she was kind and smiled).

Restaurant week review on a Monday night - Amazing food, ambience, decor and great price!  We actually came here to celebrate our friend's birthday and wanted a restaurant that was a little bit more unique and this place served that purpose. It looks like a cute mix between speakeasy and library, the walls are large bookcases and just overall decor was just super chiq.  We had a party of 14 people and were seated in the back which was definitely much more intimate and had the feeling that it was a restaurant all to ourselves.  The pre-fix menu was quite nice, there an abundance of food for the price because this is not the first restaurant week that I have ever been to. There was a full three course menu where you walked out feeling...wow I am so full. We started off with a full appetizer, my main course was a salmon - cooked to perfection and the dessert...there were three! Not three options but you got to taste all three!! There was so much desert most of us did not even eat it all. There was a chocolate lava cake, a orange sorbet and ice cream and wow...all three was phenomenal.  Would recommend coming back!

I sent my friends to this restaurant with my warmest recommendations. I visit this place often. I get very good feedback from my friends. The dishes they serve are delicious and the stuff is efficient and cooperative. Every time  we visit this place we enjoy a cheerful evening.  I recommend this place with pleasure.
Great for happy hour - $5 a pint 🇮🇪🇬🇧

Came to the Tuck Room late last night, tucked away on the top floor of a movie theater (I see what I did there), and even though it is listed as open until 2am, the kitchen closes at 11pm, 5 minutes after we got there. However, we were seated and served with all the courtesy a nice place like this deserves and the food was fantastic, the ahi tuna poke was exceptional and the s'mores dessert was the perfect way to end the day.

Had a corporate dinner here last night and it was wonderful. We had a private room, which was nice and the decor was beautiful. We had a pre-fix menu - the portions were really generous. Most of those who ordered the duck couldn’t even finish because it was a lot!  Overall, everyone had a great time and enjoyed the food. Would definitely come back again for a more casual outing. Our server was Mikala (sp?) and she was great!!

Good place, good view of brooklyn and good food. Went here for my husband's birthday with couple of friends. Love the environment and food. Waiter was nice person who took care of us and made us Negroni even thought it was not on their menu. Will be visiting again.

We would never have known that there was a restaurant up top.  The atmosphere is great and the staff were all very friendly and attentive. We visited on a Monday lunch time, and it was quite quiet. Chris, our waiter was very helpful in explaining further details on the food. I was really impressed with the food quality and portion size and would certainly return. If you are visiting Pier 17 and fancy a bite to eat at lunch time like we did, this is a great venue, very tastefully designed also.

Ok, I've given this place a few chances because of its ambience but I will not be returning. Today I ordered a charcuterie plate. I was by myself at the bar. The menu lists lardon as well as a pepper relish/Chile that should be on the plate. These two items were missing. That would be fine if they ran out, but they didn't replace those items with anything. The plate really needed something sweet to cut all the salt and fat of the meat and cheese. There wasn't even a stray grape on the plate. I figured no harm no foul -- if I ask for something -- anything -- they should be able to come up with a suitable replacement. I apologized to the bartender and asked for a "jam or jelly" or something, figuring he would understand why I was asking because I had the charcuterie plate. He looked confused and then relayed this to someone I assume to be the shift manager or bar manager. This guy laughs right in front of me and repeats  "jam or jelly??" Like it was the most ridiculous thing he'd ever heard. I never got any jam or fruit of any kind, and no one even came up to me to say sorry they didn't have anything. It was awkward especially considering I had asked. When I asked for my check the bartender gave it to me without any comment or explanation about the fruit.  This seems like a small thing but it was quite rude to have the manager just laugh at my request, and then have no one even respond to it at all. I won't be going back again unfortunately.  Side note, the specialty punches are super sugary, do not order.

I was so excited to try this place based on the reviews. The food was ok, but I left still hungry and we spent over $100. I had the chicken schnitzel which is basically a chicken cutlet which came with a small spinach salad that did have a nice taste and some kind of pickled cole slaw type thing that came in a condiment dish but did also taste good. I ordered brussel sprouts on the side because I just love those little buggers. The menu described them as cooked with salt, pepper and lemon but all I could taste was horseradish. When I addressed it with the waiter, he said they don't put horseradish on them... but there definitley was so either I'm crazy or I'm a liar. My husband and youngest also tasted the strong horseradish so that reassured me I'm neither crazy or a liar. The waiter said he would try and get me some prepared the way the menu described but he never did and never brought it back up. My youngest had the special of the day which was salmon. She really enjoyed it. Her plate came with the unusual brussel sprouts and potatoes. Oddly enough, her brussles also had a strong horseradish taste. My husband had the ribs which came with a mango habenaro sauce which he thought was a little too sweet with no taste of habenaro, but still good. His order also came with cornbread that was infused with honey and topped with goat cheese. Personally I didn't taste the cornbread taste at all, but he seemed to enjoy it and that is what matters. We all had iced tea which they make special at $6 a glass. It was ok...tasted like peach flavored unsweetened iced tea. They bring a vanilla bean liquid sweetener if you like sweeter flavored tea. I was dying to try the toffee ice cream cookie with caramel but we were informed they ran out of ice cream. By this point I was done and just wanted to leave and get some real food! What really turned me off about this place was the table behind us ordered alcoholic beverages and after not being out in 5 minutes and without the table complaining, our waiter came by and told them they're drinks were on the way and he was going to give them one of their drinks free because they had to wait. I'm not sure what to think about that, but I felt offended.  I felt he could have at least had the brussel sprouts removed from our check or given us a small percentage off...something! But no! I wouldn't recommend this place, not because of the food... But because the portions are way too small and the prices are way too high. Service started out strong and ended weak. I really can't comment on the cleanliness, because the lighting was very dim. The menu is small and not many choices. Overall, it was a bad experience for me... So there ya go.

This is a historic building beautifully renovated after hurricane Sandy. The restaurant on the third floor is modern yet historic, and gives an upscale feel with the decor and the furniture. The view is funny - you basically see car wheels and windows as they drive by on the FDR elevated highway. There’s a very intimate square table that seats eight, and a “secret door” in a bookcase that takes you to a private room. So why only three stars? Because the food is really below standard, and quite expensive. Overcooked burgers, bland salads, cold fries. And one of the worst Poké I have had this side of the pacific. If you seek drinks this will be a fun place in a historic district. If you want to eat, there are plenty better options nearby.

The Tuck Room is a nice spot located at the South street Seaport, and I have to give this location 3 stars - not because we had a bad experience, but because it was mediocre. We ordered the trio of K Town sliders. Delicious in flavor, but lacking in presentation. Our server offered us a sample of their current scotch infusion, and so we ordered a taste on the rocks. When it arrived we realized the drink was very strong, but the bartender offered to doctor it so that it was palatable. I ordered a house made Ginger beer with blood orange puree. THAT was outstanding!! They must flavor their ginger beer with cardamom and cloves and it really elevated the flavors of the ginger and blood orange. We also noticed there's a speakeasy behind the bookshelf. I give this place a 5 for decor, with an intimate yet chic setting.
